1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:17,090
In 1912, fragments from a gravel pit in Sussex seemed to give British science the fossil it wanted, a human-like skull, an ape-like jaw, a famous name Piltdown Man.

2
00:00:18,201 --> 00:00:21,085
The evidence was thin, but the story was powerful.

3
00:00:22,167 --> 00:00:26,594
It fit a brain-first theory and gave Britain its own ancient ancestor.

4
00:00:27,435 --> 00:00:37,070
Some anatomists doubted the skull and jaw belonged together, but access was limited, prestige was heavy, and the specimen kept circulating as authority.

5
00:00:37,771 --> 00:00:39,033
The fraud was not perfect.

6
00:00:39,774 --> 00:00:40,435
It was welcome.

7
00:00:41,417 --> 00:00:45,323
By 1953, tests exposed the trick.

8
00:00:45,302 --> 00:00:47,189
The skull was recent human bone.

9
00:00:47,993 --> 00:00:49,537
The jaw was from an orangutan.

10
00:00:50,200 --> 00:00:51,505
The teeth had been filed.

11
00:00:52,106 --> 00:00:53,392
The bones had been stained.

12
00:00:54,113 --> 00:00:57,365
The hoax survived because it let the field feel correct.

13
00:00:58,289 --> 00:01:01,320
The mystery fades. The receipts remain.
